column81: I believe the task involved determining patterns between diagrams. By having similar prompts but in various ways (like having king/queen and then man/woman) it determined what associations we connected between the patterns. I think it also could be used to determine any bias that the participant has. I was most confused by the first diagram with the various shapes but started to learn as the task went.
column82: I answered the questions by first looking at the various groups possible (like king, queen, woman, man) and then tried to look for any patterns (so king to man and queen to woman). Typically I assumed that the third prompt related to the first two (so I saw that man was the last prompt and seemed to be a variation of king and then applied that same variation to queen to get the pattern for woman).

column32:
I thought the questions required thinking about the relationships between objects of a similar type in different groups and among the same group. 

For example, I recognized the patterns between puppy and dog, as they are the same animal in different stages of life, and then connected the relationship between those patterns to other animals, such as cat and kitten, which are the adult and child forms of a different animal. 

In short, I think the tasks involved logical thinking and pattern recognition.
column33:

I first tried to find the connection between the first two given objects, and then I tried to see if that connection was applicable to the second group of objects.
